March 18, 1952
3903 So. Crairie Ave
Chicago 15,
Dear Mr. Caurey,
You do not know me but I would like to introduce myself. My name is Frances K Graves I am ninenteen years old. I am a student at the Roosevelt College. My major is Education. I am enrolled in a children's Literature Class. In this class we read childrens books and discuss them. We are also trying to make a peaf book of the well known Children's authors. You were my choice as top author in this field. I have read your autobiography and some of your books namely: Slapper Hooper, The Fast Sooner -- and Sam Catch.
I need a little personal information in order to complete

my research of you. I would like to know everything about your life that you feel will interest the class. Anything you wish to tell us is welcomed. If you have any pictures or book-jacket we would appreciate them to the highest. If it would not inconvenience you too much would you please fead me a list of all the books that you have written.
We are to hand in an -- of our project on March twenty-eighth. If you are not too busy I would like to have some information by them.
I am enclosing a questionnaire and a self addressed envelope. Filling out this questionnaire well give you an idea of what we need.
Please remember that whatever you send will be forever cherished by us.
Please turn over
I would be glad to answer any questions that you have. Thank you in advance (Miss) Frances R. Graves

April 15, 1 952
3903 So. Prairie
Chicago 15, Ill.
Dear Jack, How are you feeling on this very fine day? I would like to intrude on your good nature once again. I am in desperate need of a little more personal information about double underline: yew.  I was wondering if it would be possible for you to give me an appointment. I would like to visit you and take some snap shots of you and your family. If it is at all possible perhaps I could visit you some sunday afternoon. If you will give me a couple of days that you are available, I shall

try to arrange my time to fit your's. If you don't have to to write maybe you could phone me.
My telephone no. is
Oa4 - 8667
Thanking you
-- again

Frances Graves
3903 So. Prairie
Chicago 15, Ill.
Dear Jack,
Thanks loads for your cooperation. The project was a great success. I guess you thought I had forgotten to send your article. But I had been out of town attending a convention.
Give your wife my regards and thanks again for your cooperation. If I can be of any service to you let me know.
Frances Graves

Gregory, Horace

Dear Jack-               12/12/74
Writers in Revolt is a valuable, enjoyable piece of work and for a guy as interested in the literary history of the 30's as me, it is an essential part of my modest, but growing library.
Keep enjoying your reviews often too, and I look forward to the publication announcements of those fascinating memoirs you've been working on! So assiduously. When will that be?
Hope you and your wife are both well.
Respectfully,
Rogen Griffith
810 Park Dr.
Kamhakee, Fee,

Mr. Jack Couroy, Esq.
701 Fisk Ave.
Moberly, MO. 65270

Your forthcoming autobiography is of much interest to me and I hope it is coming along well! Meanwhile, I'm engaged in a history of the recent American novel - looks like I'll be years grappling with it. Enjoyed chatting with you by phone awhile back about Manfred, etc. Kasen'o best!
Roger Griffith

Kankakee, Fee
